Kenya and her international partners have done a commendable job fighting desert locusts that have been wreaking havoc in various parts of the country.  The battle has been so successful that last week Kenya declared victory against the destructive insect.  On Monday, United Nations Food and Agricultural Organisation also announced that Kenya had indeed triumphed over the locusts.  Unfortunately, the day after swarms of locusts invaded Rhamudimtu Ward in Mandera North. The war, clearly, is not yet over.  It is imperative that the government moves with speed and deals with these new swarms before they can multiply and spread out. Some counties, including Mandera, are in the jaws of drought. If locusts move further afield, they will spread despondency in equal measure.  Locusts invade parts of Mandera, day after Kenya declared free of them  Report reveals 1.5million Kenyans are facing hunger   Government should step up fight against locusts  Locusts swarm Kenya They must be stopped.   Government's measures put in place to curb the invasion of desert locusts in Kenya yet to bear fruit  Cyrus Oguna talks on Government's efforts to eradicate Kenya's desert locust invasion  Farmers count massive losses after desert locusts invaded their farms in Mbooni By Editorial | 11 hours ago By Editorial | 1 day ago By Editorial | 1 day ago By Editorial | 2 days ago